tionalists developed critiques of racism, imperialism, and nationalism in world affairs. They rejected exceptionalist frameworks and eschewed the dominant "Christian nation" imaginary as a lens through which to view U.S. foreign relations. In the intellectual history of religion and American foreign relations, Protestantism most commonly appears as an ideological ancillary to expansionism and nationalism. For God and Globe challenges this account by recovering a movement that held Christian universalism to be a check against nationalism rather than a boon to it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and international relationsxHistoryy20th century. 0aChristianity and politicszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aProtestantismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aReligious Studies. 4aU.S. History.  areligion in American life, religious nationalism, American exceptionalism, international relations, foreign policy, world affairs, interwar ecumenical movement, internationalism, Reinhold Niebuhr, politics, political science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170180140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701801423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701801/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles